<br>
18 Nov 2002<br>
<br>
The National Aeronautics &amp; Space Administration (NASA) wants the nuclear industry's help in developing new power systems, NASA Administrator Sean O'Keefe said today. Speaking at the American Nuclear Society's winter meeting in Washington, D.C., O'Keefe said NASA had asked Congress for about $1-billion over five years for its new Nuclear Systems Initiative. He said the program would focus on two major areas--furthering radioisotope power systems and fission/power/propulsion research. O'Keefe said the ultimate goal of the research activities is to develop &quot;safe, highly efficient electric propulsion systems for interplanetary spacecraft that will be powered by nuclear reactors.&quot; O'Keefe said nuclear-propelled technology would allow NASA to undertake missions &quot;inconceivable with current conventional chemical propulsion.&quot; <br>
